fuzzyIpMatch

public static boolean fuzzyIpMatch(String ipA,
                                   String ipB,
                                   int octets)
Matches two "fuzzy IPs" to each other with the specified amount of octets.

Fuzzy IPs are IPv4-addresses which may contain wildcard values. Example: 192.168.*.*. This method matches two (or one) fuzzy IP(s) to each other and return a boolean based on the result.

A simple example: the example-IP, 192.168.*.*, contains 2 fuzzy octets. Both 192.168.2.1 and 192.168.123.231 match this fuzzy IP but 123.12.2.2 does not.

Other examples: 

 IpUtils.fuzzyIpMatch("19.19.*.*", "19.19.1.1", 4); // true
 IpUtils.fuzzyIpMatch("*.*.*.*", "122.124.52.44", 4); // true
 IpUtils.fuzzyIpMatch("192.*.33.22", "192.44.33.*", 4); // true
 IpUtils.fuzzyIpMatch("31.23.88.44", 31.23.12.8", 2); // true
 IpUtils.fuzzyIpMatch("80.34.10.2", "80.*.12.3", 2; // true
 IpUtils.fuzzyIpMatch("12.15.23.5", "12.42.3.2", 2); // false

Parameters:
ipA - The first IP to matched.
ipB - The second IP to matched.
octets - The amount of octets which must be equal.
Returns:
true if the IP matches the fuzzy IP.

isValidIp

public static boolean isValidIp(String ip)
Validates if an String is a valid Ipv4 address.

Warning: This validation is very strict, validating only proper IP-addresses.

.

Examples: 

 IpUtils.isValidIp("192.0.0.256"); // false
 IpUtils.isValidIp("127.0.0.0.1"); // false
 IpUtils.isValidIp("-12.3.4.3"); // false
 IpUtils.isValidIp("a.b.c.d"); // false
 IpUtils.isValidIp("192.1.1.1"); // true

Parameters:
ip - The IP-address to validate.
Returns:
true if the IP-Address is valid.
